# {{lb|en|ambitransitive}} To form letters, words or symbols on a surface in order to communicate.
#: {{ux|en|The pupil '''wrote''' his name on the paper.}}
#: {{ux|en|Your son has been '''writing''' on the wall.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To be the author of (a book, article, poem, etc.).
#: {{ux|en|My uncle '''writes''' newspaper articles for ''The Herald''.}}
#* {{RQ:Besant Ivory Gate|chapter=Prologue|passage=Thus, when he drew up instructions in lawyer language{{nb...}}; his clerks, however, understood him very well. If he had '''written''' a love letter, or a farce, or a ''ballade'', or a story, no one, either clerks, or friends, or compositors, would have understood anything but a word here and a word there.}}
#* '''1964''', {{w|Ernest Hemingway}}, ''{{w|A Moveable Feast}}'', p. 151: 
#*: Since I had started to [[break down]] all my writing and get rid of all [[facility]] and try to make instead of describe, writing had been wonderful to do. But it was very difficult, and I did not know how I would ever '''write''' anything as long as a [[novel]]. It often took me a full morning of work to '''write''' a [[paragraph]].
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To send written information to.
#: {{ux|en|(UK) Please '''write''' to me when you get there.}}
#: {{ux|en|(US) Please '''write''' me when you get there.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To show (information, etc) in written form.
#: {{ux|en|The due day of the homework is '''written''' in the syllabus.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|title=Ghana: White Eminence|magazine=[[w:Time (magazine)|Time]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111019184337/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,891361,00.html|archivedate=19 October 2011|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher={{w|Time Inc.}}|date=30 September 1957|issn=0928-8430|oclc=224518090|passage=Ghana's motto, '''writ''' large on the gleaming white Independence Arch that overlooks the Atlantic in Accra, is "Freedom and Justice."}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|author=K. Hoole|title=The Middlesbrough–Newcastle Route of the N.E.R.|magazine=[[w:Modern Railways|Trains Illustrated]]|location=London|publisher={{w|Ian Allan Publishing}}|month=August|year=1959|page=359|issn=0141-9935|oclc=35845948|passage=The route passes over low-lying land, the only item of note being the Cerebos salt works at Greatham, where one may catch a glimpse of the smart black diesel locomotive emblazoned with the firm's name '''writ''' large.}}
# {{lb|en|ditransitive|with|[[relative clause]]}} To convey a fact to someone via writing.
#: {{ux|en|Jimmy '''wrote''' me that he needs more money.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|journal=Saturday Evening Post|date=11 March 1916|title=[advertisement] Jim Henry, Optimist
|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g54xAQAAMAAJ&pg=GBS.RA10-PA64
|text=Do you know, one man actually '''wrote''' me he thought he could almost shave with the back of the blade, the lather "mellowed" his beard so.
}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To be an author.
#* '''1964''', {{w|Ernest Hemingway}}, ''{{w|A Moveable Feast}}'', p. 151: 
#*: I said that I did not believe anyone could '''write''' any way except the very best he could '''write''' without destroying his [[talent]].
#: {{ux|en|I '''write''' for a living.}}
# {{lb|en|computing|intransitive|with {{m|en|to}}}} To record data mechanically or electronically.
#: {{ux|en|The computer '''writes''' to the disk faster than it [[reads]] from it.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|South Africa|Canada|of an exam, a document, etc.}} To [[fill in]], to [[complete]] using words.
#: {{ux|en|I was very anxious to know my score after I '''wrote''' the test.}}
# To [[impress]] [[durably]]; to [[imprint]]; to [[engrave]].
#: {{ux|en|truth '''written''' on the heart}}
# To make known by writing; to record; to prove by one's own written testimony; often used reflexively.
#* {{RQ:Marlowe Tamburlaine|1|III|iii|page=55|Thoſe walled garriſons will I ſubdue,<br>And '''write''' my ſelfe great Lord of Affrica:<br>So from the Eaſt vnto the furtheſt Weſt,<br>Shall ''Tamburlaine'' extend his puiſant arme.}}
#* {{RQ:Milton Eikonoklastes|passage=He who '''writes''' himself Martyr by his own inscription, is like an ill painter, who by writing on a shapeless picture which he hath drawn, is fain to tell passengers what shape it is, which else no man could imagine.}}
